- <span style="color:white">**Context**</span> 

- <span style="color:steelblue">**Objective**</span> aims to review the relationship between requirements engineering and software architecture and present recently proposed methodologies for documenting and handling NFRs to deliver quality software systems. 

- <span style="color:seagreen">**Method**</span> brief discussion on requirements engineering, software architectures, non-function requirements, and how the software architect handles them in ML based architectures 

- <span style="color:Tomato">**Results**</span> Three different existing methodologies (SysML, GORE, SAV) are discussed and compared in this study, that tries to address NFRs linked to ML architecture based on some NFR features. 

- <span style="color:MediumPurple">**Conclusion**</span>  Obvious lack of a general solution that targets all the requirements engineering process steps concerning NFRs in ML systems. Suggest developing a generalized solution that adequately documents and handles NFRs in ML systems.

---
> 
Khan et al. \cite{khan_handling_2022} review current RE methodologies for eliciting and documenting NFRs for ML-based \textit{Industrial Internet-of-Things (IIoT)} systems. To this end, the authors compare SysML, GORE-MLOps \cite{ishikawa_evidence-driven_2020}, and the SAV methodology \cite{pinto_requirement_2021} to drive requirement definition for autonomous systems. The paper underpins the lack of a generic RE approach that addresses the elicitation and handling of NFRs in ML-based systems.

#NFR #AI 

Documenting NFRs in ML software is considered a significant obstacle because the customers usually mention what the system is supposed to do, and the software architect is responsible for deriving the NFRs based on their experience and expertise [9]. Various studies have suggested different methods to refine and elicit NFRs from experts, such as [9] that suggest using interviews and questionnaires.

SysML Extensions for Functional and Non-Functional Requirements

Gruber et al. used SysML to model functional and non- functional needs in automotive systems, as well as the relations between them, to convey requirements visually. They were able to visualize behaviors between requirements using SysML.

GORE-MLOpsMethodology

It is proposed by Ishikawa et al. and is an extension of goal-modelling techniques to adapt requirement analysis from GORE to ML systems. GORE methodology provides improved support for modelling NFRs and quality requirements in traditional software design. This work proposes to represent uncertainty in RE for AI systems and its effects on current RE methodologies. The study focused on uncertainty and unpredictability in ML systems as it tends to affect requirement engineering analysis and decision-making. The proposed method facilitates requirement engineering activities according to the evidence-driven requirement engineering approach. It links requirement analysis in GORE with machine learning activities. Furthermore, it leverages the advantages of GORE and adapts them to machine learning. [14]

Methodology for specification, analysis, and verification in autonomous systems (SAV)

Pinto, in their research, described a methodology to drive requirement definition for autonomous systems. They, however, did not address a comprehensive list of requirements such as operational requirements, maintainability, sustainability, security, cost, and durability. Characteristics such as completeness were also not addressed. Instead, this work focuses on requirements generated from an analysis of the functional architecture of a typical system.
